1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Stop giving agents execute_sql. Give them reviewed business actions instead.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Raw database MCP can hand SQL text, table selection, filters, and write authority to the model.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Synapsor binds tenant and principal scope from trusted context, outside model arguments.

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:45,000
The reviewed contract declares visible fields, kept-out fields, bounded writes, and approval.

5
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:58,000
The model sees two semantic tools. It does not see raw SQL, credentials, approval, or apply.

6
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:10,000
The inspect tool reads one tenant-scoped customer and records evidence. The source stays unchanged.

7
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:28,000
The agent requests a plan credit. Runner stores the exact diff, evidence handle, and expected row version.

8
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Before approval, Postgres still shows zero credit. Proposal does not equal commit.

9
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:48,000
An operator reviews and approves outside the model-facing MCP surface.

10
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Guarded writeback checks approval, primary key, tenant, allowed columns, row version, and affected rows.

11
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:17,000
The receipt and replay preserve the read, evidence, proposal, approval, writeback, and result.

12
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:35,000
The same canonical contract is pushed to Synapsor Cloud as an immutable version with a server digest.

13
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:49,000
The Cloud registry exposes the reviewed boundary and exports a secret-free Runner bundle.

14
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Try the open-source Runner. Synapsor Cloud is available for design partners.
